1.1 Data Processing¶

Load the BART demand data for years 2017 and 2018 from http://64.111.127.166/origin-destination/

This data represents BART ridership by origin and destination (O-D) pairs. Each .csv file is compressed into a gz/gzip archive and contains five columns representing Day, Hour, Origin Station, Destination Station, and Trip Count. O-D pairs with a trip count of "zero" were ignored during file output to reduce file size.

I downloaded the gzip files locally and load the 2017 and 2018 data here.

In [2]:
data2017_path = "/Users/michelleliu/Documents/Hyperloop/date-hour-soo-dest-2017.csv.gz"
data2018_path = "/Users/michelleliu/Documents/Hyperloop/date-hour-soo-dest-2018.csv.gz"

data2017 = pd.read_csv(data2017_path, compression = "gzip", header=None, names = ['Day', 'Hour', 'Origin', 'Destination','Count'])
data2018 = pd.read_csv(data2018_path, compression = "gzip", header=None, names = ['Day', 'Hour', 'Origin', 'Destination','Count'])

Then because we want to plot hour by hour for 2 years, I combine the Day and the Hour to form a Datetime field, and also a field for the Origin-Destionation pair. I also put in the top 5 O-D pair to filter down the dataframe to just have informations for the 5 pairs to care about.

In [15]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(5,1, figsize=(18, 10))

color = ['m','b','r','g','y']

for i, od_pair in enumerate(top5_od_pair):
    df0 = top5_df[top5_df['O-D']==od_pair]
    axs[i].plot(df0['Datetime'], df0['Count'], color=color[i])
    axs[i].set_title("Hourly Ridership For " +top5_od_pair[i])
    axs[i].set(ylim=(0, 1000))

Here we can see an interesting pattern where POWL-BALB and BALB-POWL are pretty consistent in maintaining the average rides per hour where the other 3 O-D pairs see a larger surge and drop. We can see that the variance in the data depends on the O-D Pairs.

Note that some stations can belong to two districts. In this case, I will map it to the district with a higher number. For example, Balboa Park is partially 8 and partially 9, so I will map it to District 9.

There are 48 unique origin/destination in the data set, so here I manually map each station's acronym to the district. There are 6 stations south of San Francisco that appear in the data set that do not correspond to any district according to the website - I will group them as a new district, District 10.

Then I assign 2 new columns, Origin District (O_district) & Destination District (D_district) to every row in our dataframe with the code below.

In [16]:
#Districts from 1 to 10 in order
districts = [['CONC', 'LAFY', 'PHIL', 'WCRK'],
['NCON', 'PCTR', 'ANTC', 'PITT'],
['BAYF', 'DBRK', 'NBRK', 'ORIN', 'ROCK', 'SANL'],
['12TH', '19TH', 'COLS', 'FTVL', 'LAKE', 'OAKL'],
['CAST', 'DUBL', 'HAYW', 'WDUB'],
['FRMT', 'SHAY', 'UCTY', 'WARM'],
['ASHB', 'DELN', 'MCAR', 'PLZA', 'RICH', 'WOAK'],
['BALB', 'EMBR', 'MONT'],
['16TH', '24TH', 'CIVC', 'GLEN', 'POWL'],
['COLM', 'DALY', 'SBRN', 'SFIA', 'SSAN', 'MLBR']]

#initialize to 0 district (there should be none)
df['O_district'] = 0
df['D_district'] = 0

district_counter = 1
for d in districts:

    df.loc[df.Origin.isin(d),'O_district'] = district_counter
    df.loc[df.Destination.isin(d),'D_district'] = district_counter
    district_counter =district_counter + 1

3. Modeling - Predicting demand¶

D) BONUS: try to create a demand prediction model.¶

Given the clean data, I don't have to do too much processing - I want to predict the demand based on the O-D pair and features such as day of the week, month, hour of travel. We saw earlier that Hour and O-D pair plays a part in determining ridership. Let's do some quick EDA just to check that day of the week and month do as well.

3.1 Data Manipulation¶

I'm adding in Day of the Week and Month as features, and just sampling 50 of the top O-D pair (similar to the top 5 found in previous steps) due to memory/time constraint. There are more than 2000 unique O-D pair and the data was too large for me to test in Jupyter Notebook environment. I'm just using the 2017 dataset to train, also due to memory/time constraint.

3.3 Choosing the algorithm¶

I decided to go with Random Forest because:

  • they are easy to understand and easy to implement
  • scalable
  • the columns don't need to be scaled - no normalization needed
  • RF can capture non-linear relationships (which is evident in the EDA)
  • RF is robust against overfitting, which is also likely given the EDA

Here, I'm using scikit-learn's Random Forest Regressor.

In [40]:
#create model instance
model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 100, random_state = 42, n_jobs=-1)
#fit model
model.fit(X_train,y_train)
Out[40]:

3.4 Model Evaluation¶

Since this is not a classifier, we cannot use the ratio of number of correct predictions to the total number of prediction to determine accuracy. We can look at the absoltue error and the root mean squared error to determine model performance. We can also use Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE), a measure of prediction accuracy of a forecasting, to determine how well our model is doing.

In [41]:
#preformance metrics 
predictions = model.predict(X_test)
print('Mean Absolute Error:', mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions))
print('Mean Squared Error:', mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
print('Root Mean Squared Error:', np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)))
mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - predictions) / np.abs(y_test)))
print('Mean Absolute Percentage Error:', round(mape * 100, 2))
print('Accuracy:', round(100*(1 - mape), 2))

Mean Absolute Error: 13.5638240893
Mean Squared Error: 1087.22911879
Root Mean Squared Error: 32.9731575496
Mean Absolute Percentage Error: 51.28
Accuracy: 48.72

The model is not great, but this is just the first pass with a out of the box model (I only changed the n_estimators paramter here).

3.5 Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Next, I try to use parameter tuning to improve the performance - there is a lot of parameters within the random forest model, so I picked a few that seems the most important.

  • n_estimators = number of trees in the foreset
  • max_features = max number of features considered for splitting a node
  • max_depth = max number of levels in each decision tree
  • min_samples_split = min number of data points placed in a node before the node is split
  • min_samples_leaf = min number of data points allowed in a leaf node
  • bootstrap = method for sampling data points (with or without replacement)

3.5.1 Random Search¶

With RandomizedSearchCV, it is selecting at random a wide range of values as parameters, using 3 fold cross validation.

In [42]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 5)]
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 5)]
max_depth.append(None)
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}
print(random_grid)

best_random = rf_random.best_estimator_

#preformance metrics 
predictions = best_random .predict(X_test)
print('Mean Absolute Error:', mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions))
print('Mean Squared Error:', mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
print('Root Mean Squared Error:', np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)))
mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - predictions) / np.abs(y_test)))
print('Mean Absolute Percentage Error:', round(mape * 100, 2))
print('Accuracy:', round(100*(1 - mape), 2))

4. Conclusion¶

The random forest tree model is not great in predicting the demand given the limited feature space and out of the box hyperparameters. The data is too large for me to process in this environment, but if we were to build this in a VM where we can have multiple years of data with all the O-D pair, the model can be improved.
